Let
\begin{align}
    \vec{A} = \myvec{66\\25}, \vec{B} = \myvec{99\\69}
\end{align}
Then
\begin{align}
\norm{\vec{B}-\vec{A}}=\norm{\vec {C}}
\end{align}
\begin{align}
 \norm{\vec{C}}^2 &= \vec{C}^\top \vec{C} \\
&=  \myvec{33 \ 44} \myvec{33\\44}\\
\implies \norm{\vec{C}}=\sqrt{(33^2 + 44^2)}\\
&=55
\end{align}
